Predicting Heart Disease¶

Using a Microsoft Data Science Capstone dataset from kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/nandvard/microsoft-data-science-capstone/homeit

The goal is to predict the rate of heart disease (per 100,000 individuals) across the United States at the county-level from other socioeconomic indicators. The data is compiled from a wide range of sources and made publicly available by the United States Department of Agriculture Economic Research Service (USDA ERS).

There are 33 variables and 3198 rows in this dataset. Each row in the dataset represents a United States county.

We're trying to predict the variable heart_disease_mortality_per_100k (a positive integer) for each row of the test data set.

EDA: Results¶

Overall, this appears to be a fairly clean dataset that is should work well with some of the more complex models. It started with 34 columns (including the target) and 3198 rows. I started by looking at the column names/datatypes to find that a majority of the columns were already in percentage terms (i.e. percent adult obesity) for the prevalence of certain comorbid or demographic conditions in that particular county. There were three that were catagorical, so I looked at the distribution of the values within each of these to see if/what needed grouped. I left them alone, as each group had a significant amount of observations (<2% of total). I then looked at correlations across the entire dataset to see which columns could be eliminated/grouped. There was only two ('Large-in a metro area with at least 1 million residents or more' and 'Metro counties with at least 1 million residents or more') that were highly correlated (>90% corr), so i removed one).

After looking at distribution of the numeric columns, I looked for outliers using a boxplot visualization. Though the were several (outside of the 1.5 IQR), but they did not appear to be in error. I decided not to impute them as I planned to min/max normalize. Normalization (min/max 0-1) compressed several columns, but about half remained unchanged, as they were already in percentage terms. Bringing these all to the same scale will help many of the models to run more efficiently/effectively.

Lastly, I created split the target ('heart_disease_mortality_per_100k') as a binary at the median. This will be used to assess the models that use classification and used to predict whether counties with unknown rates are above or below average. There is also a copy that keeps the target as a continuous variable, for regression models.

Optimal KNN Parameters:¶

The model choose the nearest neighbors = 3. Our grid search also choose the Manhattan distance over the Euclidean. The last parameter it used was weighting points by the inverse of their distance. Closer neighbors of a query point will have a greater influence than neighbors which are further away.

KNN Performance:¶

The model performance was boosted signinifantly from the baseline (defaults w/ k=3) accuracy of 77.5% and captured 77% of the true positives.

The KNN model I cross validated, which takes an average of the 10 subsets (k-folds) used to create a more generalizable model and improve performance. The mean is .891, which is close to that of the model (.916). The range of accuracies is also within an expected range (from .862-.919), this gives us confidence that the model is not overfitting on the particular of data. The model also captured 90% of the true positive cases with precision of 92%. As seen in the chart (above) it also had an AUC of 0.883, which explains the relationship of True Positives to False Positives.

DT w/Bagging¶

A Bagging classifier is an ensemble meta-estimator that fits base classifiers each on random subsets of the original dataset and then aggregate their individual predictions (either by voting or by averaging) to form a final prediction. This reduces the variance by introducing randomization into its construction procedure and then making an ensemble out of it.

Extremely Random Forest Performance:¶

In extremely randomized trees (see ExtraTreesClassifier and ExtraTreesRegressor classes), randomness goes one step further in the way splits are computed. As in random forests, a random subset of candidate features is used, but instead of looking for the most discriminative thresholds, thresholds are drawn at random for each candidate feature and the best of these randomly-generated thresholds is picked as the splitting rule. This usually allows to reduce the variance of the model a bit more, at the expense of a slightly greater increase in bias.

This model produced an AUC of 0.893 is very good. The baseline had an accuracy of 89.4% and captured 89% of the true positives.

LASSO performance:¶

Using the default parameters, this model had an R^2 of 0.635 which is below the other models but still a signinifant amount of the variance explained. The advantage of the LASSO model is interpretibility of the features. It reduced the number of features from 56 to 23 and the feature weights allow hospital to know how their county received it's prediction by the feature weight. This may also help them focus on patients/habits may be best to focus on (though the true underlying cause should be analyzed).

Conclusion:¶

The best performing model across all 3 measures (Accuracy, TP recall, and AUC) was the SVM (rbf) using grid search the model (which changed C = 10, and gamma = 1). The models increased to an accuracy of 92.4% and True positive recall of 91%. Cross validation averaged 0.895 with a range of .871-.910, which a is below that of the model so we may expect this model to perform in this range when exposed to new data. As seen in the chart (above) it also had an AUC of 0.923, which explains the relationship of True Positives to False Positives.

Of the regression models, the Extremely Random Forest explained the most variance of any model with an R^2 of 0.758. However, I would reccomend the LASSO regression model for ease of interpretation. It cut the number of features in half (from 56 to 23) and still achieved an R^2 of 0.635. This may also help them focus on patients/habits may be best to focus on (though the true underlying cause should be analyzed).

from IPython.display import HTML

def hide_input_cell(self=None):
    '''
    Hides a cell's input by double-clicking on (ln()).
    
    Required Parameter(s): None
    Optional Parameter(s): None
    '''
    return HTML('''<script type="text/Javascript">
                   $("<style type='text/css'> div.input.collapse { max-height:60px; overflow:scroll;} </style>").appendTo("head");
                   $('div.prompt.input_prompt').on('dblclick', function(event) {
                       console.log("CLICKED", arguments)   
                       var c = $(event.target).closest('div.input')
                       if(c.hasClass('collapse')) {
                          c.removeClass('collapse');
                       } else {
                           c.addClass('collapse');
                       }
                     });
                   ''')
